{"title_page": "Akram Pedramnia", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=September 2019}}\n{{Orphan|date=August 2019}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Akram Pedramnia\n| image        = Akram Pedramnia.jpg\n| alt          = \n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1969|02|17}}\n| birth_place  = [[Iran]]\n| occupation   = Writer, researcher, translator, [[joycean]] scholar and physician\n| nationality  = \n| citizenship  = [[Iran]], Canada\n| education    = \n| alma_mater   = \n| period       = \n| genre        = \n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| awards       = \n| signature    = \n| website      = \n| portaldisp   = \n}}\n\n'''Akram Pedramnia''' (Persian: [[:fa:\u0627\u06a9\u0631\u0645 \u067e\u062f\u0631\u0627\u0645\u200c\u0646\u06cc\u0627|\u0627\u06a9\u0631\u0645 \u067e\u062f\u0631\u0627\u0645\u200c\u0646\u06cc\u0627]]) (February 17, 1969) is an Iranian-Canadian writer, translator, [[Joycean]] scholar,<ref>{{cite web|title=Lecture by ZJJF Scholar Akram Pedramnia: \"'Not to Change Even a Single Word': Disseminating the Persian Translation of Ulysses Under a System of Censorship\"|url=https://www.es.uzh.ch/en/scis-zjjf/eventsarchive/zjjflectureakrampedramnia.html|publisher=University of Zurich|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref> researcher, activist, and physician. She has written, researched, and translated many English novels and political articles. She resides in Canada since 1998 when she had emigrated from [[Iran]].<ref name=\"K\u00e4mpferin\"/>\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn and raised to a working class family in [[Kashan]], Pedramnia studied English literacy at the [[University of Tehran]].<ref name=\"Mehr News\"/> She was admitted then to [[Iran University of Medical Sciences]]<ref name=\"Mehr News\"/> and graduated as a physician in 1997. In Canada, she obtained a [[Health informatics]] degree from [[McMaster University]].\n\nShe is currently writing and translating about a variety of matters, including novels, literature critics, and social issues. Pedramnia has also frequently written for international Iranian newspapers and websites.\n\n== Books ==\nShe is the author of three novels in the [[Persian language]],<ref name=\"OBrien\"/> \u0646\u0641\u06cc\u0631 \u06a9\u0648\u06cc\u0631 (''Nefir Desert''),<ref name=\"Mejalehhafteh\">{{cite web |last1=\u0645\u0639\u0631\u0641\u06cc \u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628 |title=Introducing the book 'Nefir Desert' by Akram Pedramnia |url=https://mejalehhafteh.com/2011/01/14/%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%B1%D9%81%DB%8C-%DA%A9%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A8-%D9%86%D9%81%DB%8C%D8%B1-%DA%A9%D9%88%DB%8C%D8%B1-%D9%86%D9%88%D8%B4%D8%AA%D9%87-%D8%A7%DA%A9%D8%B1%D9%85-%D9%BE%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%85/ |website=Mejalehhafteh |accessdate=4 December 2019 |language=Persian |date=January 14, 2011}}</ref> \u0632\u06cc\u06af\u0648\u0631\u0627\u062a (''Ziggurat''),<ref name=\"Ghiati\"/><ref name=\"Mehr News\"/><ref name=\"Iranefarda\">{{cite news |title=\u0628\u0627\u0632\u0627\u0631\u0686\u0647 \u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628. \u0642\u0631\u0628\u0627\u0646\u06cc/ \u0628\u0647\u0627\u0631\u06a9 \u0639\u0631\u0641\u0627\u0646 (Book Market. The Victim/ Mystical Spring) |url=http://iranefardanews.com/2017/02/%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B2%D8%A7%D8%B1%DA%86%D9%87-%D9%83%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A8-%D9%82%D8%B1%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%86%DB%8C-%D8%A8%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%B1%DA%A9-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D9%81%D8%A7%D9%86/ |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=Iranefarda News |date=March 3, 2016 |language=Persian}}</ref> and \u0632\u0645\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u062a\u067e\u0647\u200c\u0647\u0627\u06cc \u0633\u0648\u0645\u0627 (''Winter on the Soma Hills''),<ref name=\"Mehr News\">{{cite news |title=\"\u0632\u06cc\u06af\u0648\u0631\u0627\u062a\" \u062f\u0648\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0628\u0647 \u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628\u200c\u0641\u0631\u0648\u0634\u06cc\u200c\u0647\u0627 \u0628\u0627\u0632\u06af\u0634\u062a (Ziggurat returned to bookstores again) |url=https://www.mehrnews.com/news/3903874/%D8%B2%DB%8C%DA%AF%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%87-%D8%A8%D9%87-%DA%A9%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A8-%D9%81%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B4%DB%8C-%D9%87%D8%A7-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B2%DA%AF%D8%B4%D8%AA |accessdate=23 November 2019 |work=Mehr News |date=14 February 2017 |location=Tehran, Iran |language=Persian}}</ref><ref name=\"Marashi\">{{cite news |last1=Marashi |first1=Mehdi |title=Evening with Mehdi Marashi |url=https://radioimontreal.com/2015/05/24/r120/ |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=Ici Montr\u00e9al (Radio Inja Montreal) |date=May 24, 2015 |language=Persian}}</ref> on themes which reveal underlying social issues in Iran.<ref name=\"K\u00e4mpferin\"/>\n\nShe has also translated into Persian texts by various authors such as [[Colm T\u00f3ib\u00edn]],<ref name=\"K\u00e4mpferin\"/> [[E. L. Doctorow]],<ref name=\"K\u00e4mpferin\"/> [[Naomi Klein]],<ref name=\"K\u00e4mpferin\"/> [[Joan London (Australian author)|Joan London]]<ref name=\"K\u00e4mpferin\"/> (''[[Gilgamesh (novel)|Gilgamesh]]''),<ref name=\"Ghiati\"/> [[Noam Chomsky]] (''[[Failed States: The Abuse of Power and the Assault on Democracy]]''),<ref name=\"OBrien\"/> [[Richard B. Wright]] (''[[Clara Callan]]''), [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]] (''[[Tender Is the Night]]'', 2009),<ref name=\"OBrien\"/><ref name=\"Ghiati\"/><ref name=\"Snaije\"/> [[Vladimir Nabokov]] (''[[Lolita]]'', 2014)<ref name=\"OBrien\"/><ref name=\"Ghiati\"/><ref name=\"Snaije\"/><ref name=\"Asymptote\"/> and [[James Joyce]] (''[[Ulysses (novel)|Ulysses]]'').<ref name=\"Ghiati\">{{cite news|last=Ghiati |first=Nasser |title='\u0644\u0648\u0644\u06cc\u062a\u0627'\u061b \u0627\u0632 \u0646\u0648\u0634\u062a\u0646 \u062a\u0627 \u062a\u0631\u062c\u0645\u0647 \u0648 \u0627\u0646\u062a\u0634\u0627\u0631 \u0628\u0647 \u0641\u0627\u0631\u0633\u06cc \u062f\u0631 \u0627\u0641\u063a\u0627\u0646\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 ('Lolita' - From Writing to Translating and Publishing into Farsi in Afghanistan)|url=http://www.bbc.com/persian/arts/2014/07/140705_l41_book_lolita_akramnia_afghanistan.shtml |date=10 July 2014 |language=Persian |work=BBC Persian News|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lolita Translation |url=http://thenabokovian.org/sites/default/files/2018-01/NABOKV-L-0025570___body.html|publisher=thenabokovian.org|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref> A translation of [[Margaret Atwood]]'s ''[[Alias Grace]]'' had not been published as of January 2019, as, according to Pedramnia, the publishers had requested cuts which she did not agree to.<ref name=\"OBrien\"/>\n\nShe received a scholarship to carry out research at the James Joyce Foundation in Zurich, to aid her translation of ''Ulysses''.<ref name=\"Snaije\"/>\n\n== Activism on censorship ==\nPedramnia is best known for her work in challenging and criticizing Iranian censorship opposing [[freedom of speech and expression]] of writers and artists. In 2013 she translated [[Vladimir Nabokov]]'s ''Lolita'' into Persian, almost sixty years after its only other Persian translation.<ref name=\"Ghiati\"/> The book was published in [[Afghanistan]], another Persian language speaking nation and Iran's neighbouring country, by a [[Kabul]]-based publisher named [[Zaryab Publication]].<ref name=\"SNN\">{{cite news |title=\u0647\u06cc\u0648\u0644\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u06a9\u0647 \u0627\u0632 \u0648\u06cc\u062a\u0631\u06cc\u0646\u200c \u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628\u200c\u0641\u0631\u0648\u0634\u06cc\u200c\u0647\u0627\u06cc \u062a\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0633\u0631 \u062f\u0631 \u0622\u200c\u0648\u0631\u062f! (Monster of Tehran Bookstore Showcase!) |url=https://snn.ir/fa/news/398319/%D9%87%DB%8C%D9%88%D9%84%D8%A7%DB%8C%DB%8C-%DA%A9%D9%87-%D8%A7%D8%B2-%D9%88%DB%8C%D8%AA%D8%B1%DB%8C%D9%86%E2%80%8C-%DA%A9%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A8%E2%80%8C%D9%81%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B4%DB%8C%E2%80%8C%D9%87%D8%A7%DB%8C-%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%B3%D8%B1-%D8%AF%D8%B1-%D8%A2%E2%80%8C%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%AF |accessdate=23 November 2019 |work=Student News Network |language=Persian}}</ref> Soon after ''Lolita'' found its way to the Iranian [[Black market|underground market]]. In response, the Iranian [[Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance|Minister of Cultural and Islamic Guidance]] declared that Pedramnia's translation is banned and has been disseminated illegally.<ref name=\"SNN\"/> The book was later published in a different format as [[samizdat]] inside Iran.<ref name=\"Asymptote\"/><ref name=\"Ghiati\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Thanks Afghanistan|url=https://nowruziran.wordpress.com/2015/02/25/reading-lolita-in-tehran-still-strictly-forbidden-but-possible-thanks-afghanistan/|publisher=Nowrouzian weblog|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref> Due to the same argument her recent work, the translation of [[James Joyce]]'s ''Ulysses'', another forbidden book, has been planned for publication in six volumes by [[Nogaam Press]], a Persian-language publisher based in London, England which aims to publish Persian writing and translation beyond the censorship concerns faced inside the country. The first volume was released in April 2019.<ref name=\"Snaije\">{{cite journal |last=Snaije |first=Olivia |title=Fourth Tehran Book Fair Uncensored Moves Next to Germany|url=https://publishingperspectives.com/2019/04/fourth-tehran-book-fair-uncensored-moves-next-to-germany-after-uk-france-opening/|work=Publishing Perspectives |date=29 April 2019|accessdate=April 10, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Asymptote\">{{cite web |last=Missaghi |first=Poupeh |date=5 April 2019|title=Weekly Dispatches from the Front Lines of World Literature|url=https://www.asymptotejournal.com/blog/2019/04/05/weekly-dispatches-from-the-frontlines-of-world-literature-108/|work=Asymptote|accessdate=April 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAn article in the ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' describes her as \"one of the strongest-willed translators active today. Confronting pernicious state-sponsored censorship, watching as dubious publishers eight time zones away put her work into print without permission or payment.\"<ref name=\"OBrien\">{{cite news |last=O'Brien |first=Peter |title=A forbidden story makes its way into Iran|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books/article-a-forbidden-story-makes-its-way-into-iran/|work=The Globe and Mail |date=4 January 2019|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Italian newspaper, ''[[Il Foglio]]'' writes: \"This (''Lolita'') is my translation sold on the streets of Tehran,\" says Akram Pedramnia at this week's ''[[The Boston Globe]]''. \"The book is forbidden, but people send me these photographs, hiding their faces, of course. And they publish these images on social platforms, showing smuggling\".<ref name=\"Meotti\">{{cite news |last1=Meotti |first1=Giulio |title=La guerra dell'Iran alla cultura |url=https://www.ilfoglio.it/esteri/2019/02/25/news/la-guerra-dell-iran-alla-cultura-239848/ |accessdate=23 November 2019 |work=Il Foglio |date=25 February 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191119100249/https://www.ilfoglio.it/esteri/2019/02/25/news/la-guerra-dell-iran-alla-cultura-239848/ |archivedate=19 November 2019 |language=Italian}}</ref>\n\nA German language newspaper ''[[Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung]]'' says: \u201cHer translations are distributed as pirated or over the Internet without her earning a cent \u2013 but that does not bother Akram Pedramnia. She is even pleased. Thanks to her, Iranian readers can read ''Lolita'' or ''Tender Is the Night''\".<ref name=\"K\u00e4mpferin\">{{cite news |title=K\u00e4mpferin gegen das Diktat der Zensur (Fighter against the dictates of censorship) |date=4 July 2017 |url=https://www.nzz.ch/feuilleton/wie-man-iranische-zensoren-an-der-nase-herumfuehrt-ld.1486736|work=Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung |language=German |accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n*Scholarship: [[James Joyce Foundation]], Zurich, 2019<ref name=\"Snaije\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Joyce Translation Scholarship and Looren Residency 2020|url=https://www.joycefoundation.ch/foundation-scholars/|publisher=ZURICH JAMES JOYCE FOUNDATION|accessdate=February 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*Translation Grant: Literature Ireland for Persian translation of ''Ulysses''\n\n'''Essays and lectures'''\n*James Joyce Symposium, Antwerp, 2018 (Lecture)<ref>{{cite web |title=THE ART OF JAMES JOYCE The 26th International James Joyce Symposium 11\u201316 June 2018 Symposium Programme |website=Antwerp University|url=http://uahost.uantwerpen.be/joyce2018/wp-content/files_joyce2018/2018/06/schedule.pdf|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[University College Dublin]], Summer, 2018 (Lecture)<ref>{{cite web|title=Dublin James Joyce Summer School 2018\n|url=https://www.ucd.ie/englishdramafilm/research/jamesjoyceresearchcentre/jjrc-dublinjamesjoycesummerschool/dublinjamesjoycesummerschool2018/|work=Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung|accessdate=July 7, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[James Joyce Foundation]], Zurich, 2019 (Lecture)<ref>{{cite web|title=Lecture by ZJJF Scholar Akram Pedramnia: \"'Not to Change Even a Single Word': Disseminating the Persian Translation of Ulysses Under a System of Censorship\"\n|url=https://www.es.uzh.ch/en/scis-zjjf/eventsarchive/zjjflectureakrampedramnia.html|publisher=University of Zurich|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*James Joyce Symposium, Mexico City, 2019 (Lecture)<ref>{{cite web|title=Lecture by Akram Pedramnia |url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/95f712_82983667257a4752b079701633050bbe.pdf|publisher=wixstatic.com|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*''Dublin James Joyce Journal'', 2017 (Essay)<ref>{{cite web|title= 'Pleasure or pain, is it?': Translating Ulysses into Persian |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/715591/pdf|work=Dublin James Joyce Journal|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Free University of Berlin]] Bulletin, 2019 (Essay)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Iranian physicians]]\n[[Category:Iranian women writers]]\n[[Category:Iranian translators]]\n[[Category:Iranian literary critics]]\n[[Category:Iranian women poets]]\n[[Category:Iranian women novelists]]\n[[Category:Iranian novelists]]\n[[Category:English\u2013Persian translators]]\n[[Category:University of Tehran alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Kashan]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:All articles with unsourced statements]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=September 2019}}\n{{Orphan|date=August 2019}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Akram Pedramnia\n| image        = Akram Pedramnia.jpg\n| alt          = \n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1969|02|17}}\n| birth_place  = [[Iran]]\n| occupation   = Writer, researcher, translator, [[joycean]] scholar and physician\n| nationality  = \n| citizenship  = [[Iran]], Canada\n| education    = \n| alma_mater   = \n| period       = \n| genre        = \n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| awards       = \n| signature    = \n| website      = \n| portaldisp   = \n}}\n\n'''Akram Pedramnia''' (Persian: [[:fa:\u0627\u06a9\u0631\u0645 \u067e\u062f\u0631\u0627\u0645\u200c\u0646\u06cc\u0627|\u0627\u06a9\u0631\u0645 \u067e\u062f\u0631\u0627\u0645\u200c\u0646\u06cc\u0627]]) (February 17, 1969) is an Iranian-Canadian writer, translator, [[Joycean]] scholar,<ref>{{cite web|title=Lecture by ZJJF Scholar Akram Pedramnia: \"'Not to Change Even a Single Word': Disseminating the Persian Translation of Ulysses Under a System of Censorship\"|url=https://www.es.uzh.ch/en/scis-zjjf/eventsarchive/zjjflectureakrampedramnia.html|publisher=University of Zurich|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref> researcher, activist, and physician. She has written, researched, and translated many English novels and political articles. She resides in Canada since 1998 when she had emigrated from [[Iran]].<ref name=\"K\u00e4mpferin\"/>\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn and raised to a working class family in [[Kashan]], Pedramnia studied English literacy at the [[University of Tehran]].<ref name=\"Mehr News\"/> She was admitted then to [[Iran University of Medical Sciences]]<ref name=\"Mehr News\"/> and graduated as a physician in 1997. In Canada, she obtained a [[Health informatics]] degree from [[McMaster University]].\n\nShe is currently writing and translating about a variety of matters, including novels, literature critics, and social issues. Pedramnia has also frequently written for international Iranian newspapers and websites.\n\n== Books ==\nShe is the author of three novels in the [[Persian language]],<ref name=\"OBrien\"/> \u0646\u0641\u06cc\u0631 \u06a9\u0648\u06cc\u0631 (''Nefir Desert''),<ref name=\"Mejalehhafteh\">{{cite web |last1=\u0645\u0639\u0631\u0641\u06cc \u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628 |title=Introducing the book 'Nefir Desert' by Akram Pedramnia |url=https://mejalehhafteh.com/2011/01/14/%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%B1%D9%81%DB%8C-%DA%A9%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A8-%D9%86%D9%81%DB%8C%D8%B1-%DA%A9%D9%88%DB%8C%D8%B1-%D9%86%D9%88%D8%B4%D8%AA%D9%87-%D8%A7%DA%A9%D8%B1%D9%85-%D9%BE%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%85/ |website=Mejalehhafteh |accessdate=4 December 2019 |language=Persian |date=January 14, 2011}}</ref> \u0632\u06cc\u06af\u0648\u0631\u0627\u062a (''Ziggurat''),<ref name=\"Ghiati\"/><ref name=\"Mehr News\"/><ref name=\"Iranefarda\">{{cite news |title=\u0628\u0627\u0632\u0627\u0631\u0686\u0647 \u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628. \u0642\u0631\u0628\u0627\u0646\u06cc/ \u0628\u0647\u0627\u0631\u06a9 \u0639\u0631\u0641\u0627\u0646 (Book Market. The Victim/ Mystical Spring) |url=http://iranefardanews.com/2017/02/%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B2%D8%A7%D8%B1%DA%86%D9%87-%D9%83%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A8-%D9%82%D8%B1%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%86%DB%8C-%D8%A8%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%B1%DA%A9-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D9%81%D8%A7%D9%86/ |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=Iranefarda News |date=March 3, 2016 |language=Persian}}</ref> and \u0632\u0645\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u062a\u067e\u0647\u200c\u0647\u0627\u06cc \u0633\u0648\u0645\u0627 (''Winter on the Soma Hills''),<ref name=\"Mehr News\">{{cite news |title=\"\u0632\u06cc\u06af\u0648\u0631\u0627\u062a\" \u062f\u0648\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0628\u0647 \u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628\u200c\u0641\u0631\u0648\u0634\u06cc\u200c\u0647\u0627 \u0628\u0627\u0632\u06af\u0634\u062a (Ziggurat returned to bookstores again) |url=https://www.mehrnews.com/news/3903874/%D8%B2%DB%8C%DA%AF%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%87-%D8%A8%D9%87-%DA%A9%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A8-%D9%81%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B4%DB%8C-%D9%87%D8%A7-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B2%DA%AF%D8%B4%D8%AA |accessdate=23 November 2019 |work=Mehr News |date=14 February 2017 |location=Tehran, Iran |language=Persian}}</ref><ref name=\"Marashi\">{{cite news |last1=Marashi |first1=Mehdi |title=Evening with Mehdi Marashi |url=https://radioimontreal.com/2015/05/24/r120/ |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=Ici Montr\u00e9al (Radio Inja Montreal) |date=May 24, 2015 |language=Persian}}</ref> on themes which reveal underlying social issues in Iran.<ref name=\"K\u00e4mpferin\"/>\n\nShe has also translated into Persian texts by various authors such as [[Colm T\u00f3ib\u00edn]],<ref name=\"K\u00e4mpferin\"/> [[E. L. Doctorow]],<ref name=\"K\u00e4mpferin\"/> [[Naomi Klein]],<ref name=\"K\u00e4mpferin\"/> [[Joan London (Australian author)|Joan London]]<ref name=\"K\u00e4mpferin\"/> (''[[Gilgamesh (novel)|Gilgamesh]]''),<ref name=\"Ghiati\"/> [[Noam Chomsky]] (''[[Failed States: The Abuse of Power and the Assault on Democracy]]''),<ref name=\"OBrien\"/> [[Richard B. Wright]] (''[[Clara Callan]]''), [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]] (''[[Tender Is the Night]]'', 2009),<ref name=\"OBrien\"/><ref name=\"Ghiati\"/><ref name=\"Snaije\"/> [[Vladimir Nabokov]] (''[[Lolita]]'', 2014)<ref name=\"OBrien\"/><ref name=\"Ghiati\"/><ref name=\"Snaije\"/><ref name=\"Asymptote\"/> and [[James Joyce]] (''[[Ulysses (novel)|Ulysses]]'').<ref name=\"Ghiati\">{{cite news|last=Ghiati |first=Nasser |title='\u0644\u0648\u0644\u06cc\u062a\u0627'\u061b \u0627\u0632 \u0646\u0648\u0634\u062a\u0646 \u062a\u0627 \u062a\u0631\u062c\u0645\u0647 \u0648 \u0627\u0646\u062a\u0634\u0627\u0631 \u0628\u0647 \u0641\u0627\u0631\u0633\u06cc \u062f\u0631 \u0627\u0641\u063a\u0627\u0646\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 ('Lolita' - From Writing to Translating and Publishing into Farsi in Afghanistan)|url=http://www.bbc.com/persian/arts/2014/07/140705_l41_book_lolita_akramnia_afghanistan.shtml |date=10 July 2014 |language=Persian |work=BBC Persian News|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lolita Translation |url=http://thenabokovian.org/sites/default/files/2018-01/NABOKV-L-0025570___body.html|publisher=thenabokovian.org|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref> A translation of [[Margaret Atwood]]'s ''[[Alias Grace]]'' had not been published as of January 2019, as, according to Pedramnia, the publishers had requested cuts which she did not agree to.<ref name=\"OBrien\"/>\n\nShe received a scholarship to carry out research at the James Joyce Foundation in Zurich, to aid her translation of ''Ulysses''.<ref name=\"Snaije\"/>\n\n== Activism on censorship ==\nPedramnia is best known for her work in challenging and criticizing Iranian censorship opposing [[freedom of speech and expression]] of writers and artists. In 2013 she translated [[Vladimir Nabokov]]\u2019s ''Lolita'' into Persian, almost sixty years after its only other Persian translation.<ref name=\"Ghiati\"/> The book was published in [[Afghanistan]], another Persian language speaking nation and Iran's neighbouring country, by a [[Kabul]]-based publisher named [[Zaryab Publication]].<ref name=\"SNN\">{{cite news |title=\u0647\u06cc\u0648\u0644\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u06a9\u0647 \u0627\u0632 \u0648\u06cc\u062a\u0631\u06cc\u0646\u200c \u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628\u200c\u0641\u0631\u0648\u0634\u06cc\u200c\u0647\u0627\u06cc \u062a\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0633\u0631 \u062f\u0631 \u0622\u200c\u0648\u0631\u062f! (Monster of Tehran Bookstore Showcase!) |url=https://snn.ir/fa/news/398319/%D9%87%DB%8C%D9%88%D9%84%D8%A7%DB%8C%DB%8C-%DA%A9%D9%87-%D8%A7%D8%B2-%D9%88%DB%8C%D8%AA%D8%B1%DB%8C%D9%86%E2%80%8C-%DA%A9%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A8%E2%80%8C%D9%81%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B4%DB%8C%E2%80%8C%D9%87%D8%A7%DB%8C-%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%B3%D8%B1-%D8%AF%D8%B1-%D8%A2%E2%80%8C%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%AF |accessdate=23 November 2019 |work=Student News Network |language=Persian}}</ref> Soon after ''Lolita'' found its way to the Iranian [[Black market|underground market]]. In response, the Iranian [[Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance|Minister of Cultural and Islamic Guidance]] declared that Pedramnia's translation is banned and has been disseminated illegally.<ref name=\"SNN\"/> The book was later published in a different format as [[samizdat]] inside Iran.<ref name=\"Asymptote\"/><ref name=\"Ghiati\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Thanks Afghanistan|url=https://nowruziran.wordpress.com/2015/02/25/reading-lolita-in-tehran-still-strictly-forbidden-but-possible-thanks-afghanistan/|publisher=Nowrouzian weblog|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref> Due to the same argument her recent work, the translation of [[James Joyce]]\u2019s ''Ulysses'', another forbidden book, has been planned for publication in six volumes by [[Nogaam Press]], a Persian-language publisher based in London, England which aims to publish Persian writing and translation beyond the censorship concerns faced inside the country. The first volume was released on April 2019.<ref name=\"Snaije\">{{cite journal |last=Snaije |first=Olivia |title=Fourth Tehran Book Fair Uncensored Moves Next to Germany|url=https://publishingperspectives.com/2019/04/fourth-tehran-book-fair-uncensored-moves-next-to-germany-after-uk-france-opening/|work=Publishing Perspectives |date=29 April 2019|accessdate=April 10, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Asymptote\">{{cite web |last=Missaghi |first=Poupeh |date=5 April 2019|title=Weekly Dispatches from the Front Lines of World Literature|url=https://www.asymptotejournal.com/blog/2019/04/05/weekly-dispatches-from-the-frontlines-of-world-literature-108/|work=Asymptote|accessdate=April 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAn article in the ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' describes her as \"one of the strongest-willed translators active today. Confronting pernicious state-sponsored censorship, watching as dubious publishers eight time zones away put her work into print without permission or payment.\"<ref name=\"OBrien\">{{cite news |last=O'Brien |first=Peter |title=A forbidden story makes its way into Iran|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books/article-a-forbidden-story-makes-its-way-into-iran/|work=The Globe and Mail |date=4 January 2019|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Italian newspaper, ''[[Il Foglio]]'' writes: \"This (''Lolita'') is my translation sold on the streets of Tehran,\" says Akram Pedramnia at this week's ''[[The Boston Globe]]''. \"The book is forbidden, but people send me these photographs, hiding their faces, of course. And they publish these images on social platforms, showing smuggling\".<ref name=\"Meotti\">{{cite news |last1=Meotti |first1=Giulio |title=La guerra dell'Iran alla cultura |url=https://www.ilfoglio.it/esteri/2019/02/25/news/la-guerra-dell-iran-alla-cultura-239848/ |accessdate=23 November 2019 |work=Il Foglio |date=25 February 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191119100249/https://www.ilfoglio.it/esteri/2019/02/25/news/la-guerra-dell-iran-alla-cultura-239848/ |archivedate=19 November 2019 |language=Italian}}</ref>\n\nA German language newspaper ''[[Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung]]'' says: \u201cHer translations are distributed as pirated or over the Internet without her earning a cent \u2013 but that does not bother Akram Pedramnia. She is even pleased. Thanks to her, Iranian readers can read ''Lolita'' or ''Tender Is the Night''\".<ref name=\"K\u00e4mpferin\">{{cite news |title=K\u00e4mpferin gegen das Diktat der Zensur (Fighter against the dictates of censorship) |date=4 July 2017 |url=https://www.nzz.ch/feuilleton/wie-man-iranische-zensoren-an-der-nase-herumfuehrt-ld.1486736|work=Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung |language=German |accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n*Scholarship: [[James Joyce Foundation]], Zurich, 2019<ref name=\"Snaije\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Joyce Translation Scholarship and Looren Residency 2020|url=https://www.joycefoundation.ch/foundation-scholars/|publisher=ZURICH JAMES JOYCE FOUNDATION|accessdate=February 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*Translation Grant: Literature Ireland for Persian translation of ''Ulysses''\n\n'''Essays and lectures'''\n*James Joyce Symposium, Antwerp, 2018 (Lecture)<ref>{{cite web |title=THE ART OF JAMES JOYCE The 26th International James Joyce Symposium 11\u201316 June 2018 Symposium Programme |website=Antwerp University|url=http://uahost.uantwerpen.be/joyce2018/wp-content/files_joyce2018/2018/06/schedule.pdf|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[University College Dublin]], Summer, 2018 (Lecture)<ref>{{cite web|title=Dublin James Joyce Summer School 2018\n|url=https://www.ucd.ie/englishdramafilm/research/jamesjoyceresearchcentre/jjrc-dublinjamesjoycesummerschool/dublinjamesjoycesummerschool2018/|work=Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung|accessdate=July 7, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[James Joyce Foundation]], Zurich, 2019 (Lecture)<ref>{{cite web|title=Lecture by ZJJF Scholar Akram Pedramnia: \"'Not to Change Even a Single Word': Disseminating the Persian Translation of Ulysses Under a System of Censorship\"\n|url=https://www.es.uzh.ch/en/scis-zjjf/eventsarchive/zjjflectureakrampedramnia.html|publisher=Univerity of Zurich|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*James Joyce Symposium, Mexico City, 2019 (Lecture)<ref>{{cite web|title=Lecture by Akram Pedramnia |url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/95f712_82983667257a4752b079701633050bbe.pdf|publisher=wixstatic.com|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*''Dublin James Joyce Journal'', 2017 (Essay)<ref>{{cite web|title= 'Pleasure or pain, is it?': Translating Ulysses into Persian |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/715591/pdf|work=Dublin James Joyce Journal|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Free University of Berlin]] Bulletin, 2019 (Essay)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Iranian physicians]]\n[[Category:Iranian women writers]]\n[[Category:Iranian translators]]\n[[Category:Iranian literary critics]]\n[[Category:Iranian women poets]]\n[[Category:Iranian women novelists]]\n[[Category:Iranian novelists]]\n[[Category:English\u2013Persian translators]]\n[[Category:University of Tehran alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Kashan]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:All articles with unsourced statements]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to Canada]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing, replaced: on April 2019 \u2192 in April 2019, Univerity \u2192 University, ]]\u2019s \u2192 ]]'s (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akram_Pedramnia"}
{"title_page": "Jim Gant", "text_new": "'''Jim Gant''' is a former [[United States Army Special Forces]] officer.  He served for over 50 months in combat in Iraq and Afghanistan and was wounded seven times.<ref name=\"ABC\"/> He was awarded a [[Silver Star]] for his actions in the [[Iraq War]] in 2007, and wrote an influential monograph on Afghanistan titled ''One Tribe at a Time: A Strategy for Success in Afghanistan''.  Following his last deployment in 2010\u201312, he was relieved of command and forced to retire after conducting an extramarital affair with reporter [[Ann Scott Tyson]] at his combat outpost in [[Kunar Province]], [[Afghanistan]].  \n\n==Military career==\nGant grew up in [[Las Cruces, New Mexico|Las Cruces]], [[New Mexico]].<ref name=\"Tyson2010\"/>  He enlisted in the Army after high school and because a Special Forces communications sergeant, participating in the [[Gulf War]].<ref name=\"Tyson2010\"/>  He later became an officer and deployed as a captain to Afghanistan in 2003\u20134 and Iraq in 2006\u20137.<ref name=\"Tyson2010\"/>  Leading Operational Detachment Alpha 316, Gant conducted operations in [[Mangwal, Afghanistan|Mangwal]] in [[Kunar Province]] and built strong relationships with the [[Mohmand tribe]], especially the tribal chief, Malik Noor Afzal.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{Cite web| last = News| first = A. B. C.| title = Top Green Beret Officer Forced to Resign Over Affair With WaPo Reporter| work = ABC News| accessdate = 2020-04-22| url = https://abcnews.go.com/Blotter/jim-gant-top-green-beret-officer-forced-resign/story?id=24266710}}</ref> On 11 December 2006, Gant's Special Forces team was attacked in a complex ambush on the road between [[Balad, Iraq|Balad]] and [[Baghdad]] in [[Iraq]].<ref name=\"Tyson2007\"/> On 3  May 2007, Gant was awarded a [[Silver Star]] for valor for his actions during the 2006 ambush.<ref name=\"Tyson2007\">{{Cite news| issn = 0190-8286| title = The Insurgents' Increasingly Complex Tactics in Ambushes| accessdate = 2020-04-22| date = 2007-06-03| url = http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/graphic/2007/06/03/GR2007060300182.html}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he wrote an influential paper titled ''One Tribe at a Time: A Strategy for Success in Afghanistan''.<ref name=\"Time\">{{Cite web| title = The Fall of the Green Berets\u2019 Lawrence of Afghanistan {{!}} Time| accessdate = 2020-04-22| url = https://time.com/2921469/the-fall-of-the-green-berets-lawrence-of-afghanistan/}}</ref>  The paper argued that the United States should leverage the [[Pashtuns|Pashtun]] tribal system in Afghanistan by creating \"Tribal Engagement Teams\" who would embed at the village level and work with locals to build security.<ref name=\"Murtazashvili2016\">{{cite book|author=Jennifer Brick Murtazashvili|title=Informal Order and the State in Afghanistan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SO-7CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA192|date=21 April 2016|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-11399-2|pages=192}}</ref><ref name=\"Tyson2010\">{{Cite news| issn = 0190-8286| last = Tyson| first = Ann Scott| title = Jim Gant, the Green Beret who could win the war in Afghanistan| accessdate = 2020-04-22| date = 2010-01-17| url = http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/15/AR2010011502203.html}}</ref> General [[David Petraeus]] called the paper \"very impressive,\" and General [[Stanley McChrystal]] distributed it to all commanders in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"Tyson2010\">{{Cite news| issn = 0190-8286| last = Tyson| first = Ann Scott| title = Jim Gant, the Green Beret who could win the war in Afghanistan| accessdate = 2020-04-22| date = 2010-01-17| url = http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/15/AR2010011502203.html}}</ref>\n\n===Final deployment===\nIn June 2010,<ref name=\"Huffpost\">{{Cite web| last = Wood| first = David| title = The Green Beret Whose Strategy Could Have Saved Afghanistan, But Not His Career| work = HuffPost| accessdate = 2020-04-22| date = 0400| url = https://www.huffpost.com/entry/afghanistan-jim-gant-american-spartan_n_5008520}}</ref> Gant began a second Afghanistan deployment, returning to the village of Mangwal where he had served in 2003.<ref name=\"ABC\"/> In September 2010, a  newspaper reporter, [[Ann Scott Tyson]], took a leave of absence from the Washington Post and went to Kunar to live with him there for nine months, in violation of military regulations.<ref name=\"Huffpost\"/>  Gant and his unit built relationships with the tribes by wearing traditional Afghan clothing instead of uniforms and learning [[Pashto]].<ref name=\"ABC\"/> He remained in Kunar for 22 months and achieved significant operational success. General Petraueus called him \"the perfect counterinsurgent\" and compared him favorably to [[T. E. Lawrence]], calling him \"Lawrence of Afghanistan.\"<ref>{{Cite web| title = Report: Petraeus Hails 'Lawrence of Afghanistan' {{!}} Military.com| accessdate = 2020-04-22| url = https://www.military.com/daily-news/2014/07/01/report-petraeus-hails-lawrence-of-afghanistan.html}}</ref>  By the middle of 2011, he had recruited 1,300 [[Afghan Local Police]].<ref name=\"Huffpost\"/> At the same time, he engaged in unorthodox behavior such as ritually cutting himself and telling his soldiers that, \"I believe in the wrathful God of combat. I believe in [[Hecate]].\"<ref>{{Cite web| title = The Rise and Fall of Major Jim Gant - War on the Rocks| accessdate = 2020-04-22| url = https://warontherocks.com/2014/04/the-rise-and-fall-of-major-jim-gant/}}</ref> He drank alcohol during the deployment, which is prohibited by Army regulations, and \"self-medicated\" with pain medication.<ref name=\"ABC\"/> In early 2012, Gant moved to the nearby village of Chowkay as part of an effort to win over the [[Safi (Pashtun tribe)|Safi]] tribe.<ref name=\"ABC\"/>  There he came in contact with First Lieutenant Thomas Roberts, who reported to his chain of command that Gant was engaging in \"immoral and illegal activities and actions.\"<ref name=\"ABC\"/>  After the subsequent investigation he was relieved of command, demoted to the rank of captain, and given an official reprimand by Lieutenant General [[John F. Mulholland, Jr.|John Mulholland]].<ref name=\"ABC\"/> He retired from the military soon afterwards.  His actions led him to be compared to [[Colonel Kurtz]] from the 1979 film ''[[Apocalypse Now]]''.<ref name=\"Time\"/> In 2014, Tyson wrote a book about Gant titled ''American Spartan: The Promise, the Mission, and the Betrayal of Special Forces Major Jim Gant''.<ref>{{Cite web| title = \u2018American Spartan \u2019 by Ann Scott Tyson, about Maj. Jim Gant\u2019s mission in Afghanistan| work = Washington Post| accessdate = 2020-04-22| url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/american-spartan--by-ann-scott-tyson-about-maj-jim-gants-mission-in-afghanistan/2014/03/28/4440187e-aac8-11e3-adbc-888c8010c799_story.html}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/report/2009/2009_one_tribe_at_a_time.pdf ''One Tribe at a Time'' \u2013 Jim Gant]\n\n[[Category:American army personnel of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Jim Gant''' is a former [[United States Army Special Forces]] officer.  He served for over 50 months in combat in Iraq and Afghanistan and was wounded seven times.<ref name=\"ABC\"/> He was awarded a [[Silver Star]] for his actions in the [[Iraq War]] in 2007, and wrote an influential monograph on Afghanistan titled ''One Tribe at a Time: A Strategy for Success in Afghanistan''.  Following his last deployment in 2010\u201312, he was relieved of command and forced to retire after conducting an extramarital affair with reporter [[Ann Scott Tyson]] at his combat outpost in [[Kunar Province]], [[Afghanistan]].  \n\n==Military career==\nGant grew up in [[Las Cruces]], [[New Mexico]].<ref name=\"Tyson2010\"/>  He enlisted in the Army after high school and because a Special Forces communications sergeant, participating in the [[Gulf War]].<ref name=\"Tyson2010\"/>  He later became an officer and deployed as a captain to Afghanistan in 2003\u20134 and Iraq in 2006\u20137.<ref name=\"Tyson2010\"/>  Leading Operational Detachment Alpha 316, Gant conducted operations in [[Mangwal, Afghanistan|Mangwal]] in [[Kunar Province]] and built strong relationships with the [[Mohmand tribe]], especially the tribal chief, Malik Noor Afzal.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{Cite web| last = News| first = A. B. C.| title = Top Green Beret Officer Forced to Resign Over Affair With WaPo Reporter| work = ABC News| accessdate = 2020-04-22| url = https://abcnews.go.com/Blotter/jim-gant-top-green-beret-officer-forced-resign/story?id=24266710}}</ref> On 11 December 2006, Gant's Special Forces team was attacked in a complex ambush on the road between [[Balad]] and [[Baghdad]] in [[Iraq]].<ref name=\"Tyson2007\"/> On 3  May 2007, Gant was awarded a [[Silver Star]] for valor for his actions during the 2006 ambush.<ref name=\"Tyson2007\">{{Cite news| issn = 0190-8286| title = The Insurgents' Increasingly Complex Tactics in Ambushes| accessdate = 2020-04-22| date = 2007-06-03| url = http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/graphic/2007/06/03/GR2007060300182.html}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he wrote an influential paper titled ''One Tribe at a Time: A Strategy for Success in Afghanistan''.<ref name=\"Time\">{{Cite web| title = The Fall of the Green Berets\u2019 Lawrence of Afghanistan {{!}} Time| accessdate = 2020-04-22| url = https://time.com/2921469/the-fall-of-the-green-berets-lawrence-of-afghanistan/}}</ref>  The paper argued that the United States should leverage the [[Pashtun]] tribal system in Afghanistan by creating \"Tribal Engagement Teams\" who would embed at the village level and work with locals to build security.<ref name=\"Murtazashvili2016\">{{cite book|author=Jennifer Brick Murtazashvili|title=Informal Order and the State in Afghanistan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SO-7CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA192|date=21 April 2016|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-11399-2|pages=192}}</ref><ref name=\"Tyson2010\">{{Cite news| issn = 0190-8286| last = Tyson| first = Ann Scott| title = Jim Gant, the Green Beret who could win the war in Afghanistan| accessdate = 2020-04-22| date = 2010-01-17| url = http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/15/AR2010011502203.html}}</ref> General [[David Petraeus]] called the paper \"very impressive,\" and General [[Stanley McChrystal]] distributed it to all commanders in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"Tyson2010\">{{Cite news| issn = 0190-8286| last = Tyson| first = Ann Scott| title = Jim Gant, the Green Beret who could win the war in Afghanistan| accessdate = 2020-04-22| date = 2010-01-17| url = http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/15/AR2010011502203.html}}</ref>\n\n===Final deployment===\nIn June 2010,<ref name=\"Huffpost\">{{Cite web| last = Wood| first = David| title = The Green Beret Whose Strategy Could Have Saved Afghanistan, But Not His Career| work = HuffPost| accessdate = 2020-04-22| date = 0400| url = https://www.huffpost.com/entry/afghanistan-jim-gant-american-spartan_n_5008520}}</ref> Gant began a second Afghanistan deployment, returning to the village of Mangwal where he had served in 2003.<ref name=\"ABC\"/> In September 2010, a  newspaper reporter, [[Ann Scott Tyson]], took a leave of absence from the Washington Post and went to Kunar to live with him there for nine months, in violation of military regulations.<ref name=\"Huffpost\"/>  Gant and his unit built relationships with the tribes by wearing traditional Afghan clothing instead of uniforms and learning [[Pashto]].<ref name=\"ABC\"/> He remained in Kunar for 22 months and achieved significant operational success. General Petraueus called him \"the perfect counterinsurgent\" and compared him favorably to [[T. E. Lawrence]], calling him \"Lawrence of Afghanistan.\"<ref>{{Cite web| title = Report: Petraeus Hails 'Lawrence of Afghanistan' {{!}} Military.com| accessdate = 2020-04-22| url = https://www.military.com/daily-news/2014/07/01/report-petraeus-hails-lawrence-of-afghanistan.html}}</ref>  By the middle of 2011, he had recruited 1,300 [[Afghan Local Police]].<ref name=\"Huffpost\"/> At the same time, he engaged in unorthodox behavior such as ritually cutting himself and telling his soldiers that, \"I believe in the wrathful God of combat. I believe in [[Hecate]].\"<ref>{{Cite web| title = The Rise and Fall of Major Jim Gant - War on the Rocks| accessdate = 2020-04-22| url = https://warontherocks.com/2014/04/the-rise-and-fall-of-major-jim-gant/}}</ref> He drank alcohol during the deployment, which is prohibited by Army regulations, and \"self-medicated\" with pain medication.<ref name=\"ABC\"/> In early 2012, Gant moved to the nearby village of Chowkay as part of an effort to win over the [[Safi (Pashtun tribe)|Safi]] tribe.<ref name=\"ABC\"/>  There he came in contact with First Lieutenant Thomas Roberts, who reported to his chain of command that Gant was engaging in \"immoral and illegal activities and actions.\"<ref name=\"ABC\"/>  After the subsequent investigation he was relieved of command, demoted to the rank of captain, and given an official reprimand by Lieutenant General [[John Mulholland]].<ref name=\"ABC\"/> He retired from the military soon afterwards.  His actions led him to be compared to [[Colonel Kurtz]] from the 1979 film ''[[Apocalypse Now]]''.<ref name=\"Time\"/> In 2014, Tyson wrote a book about Gant titled ''American Spartan: The Promise, the Mission, and the Betrayal of Special Forces Major Jim Gant''.<ref>{{Cite web| title = \u2018American Spartan \u2019 by Ann Scott Tyson, about Maj. Jim Gant\u2019s mission in Afghanistan| work = Washington Post| accessdate = 2020-04-22| url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/american-spartan--by-ann-scott-tyson-about-maj-jim-gants-mission-in-afghanistan/2014/03/28/4440187e-aac8-11e3-adbc-888c8010c799_story.html}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/report/2009/2009_one_tribe_at_a_time.pdf ''One Tribe at a Time'' \u2013 Jim Gant]\n\n[[Category:American army personnel of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Las Cruces\u2192Las Cruces, New Mexico,Balad\u2192Balad, Iraq,Pashtun\u2192Pashtuns,John Mulholland\u2192John F. Mulholland, Jr.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jim_Gant"}
{"title_page": "Cathy O'Brien (conspiracy theorist)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name   = Cathy O'Brien\n| image     = \n| image_size     = 150px\n| caption  = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1957|12|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Muskegon, Michigan]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| known_for = Critically thinking, statements alleging victimization by ''Project Monarch''\n| education      =\n| occupation     = Writer, speaker\n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| spouse         = Mark Phillips\n| parents        = Earl M. O'Brien<br>Carol O'Brien (n\u00e9e Tanis)\n| children       = Kelly O'Brien\n| website = http://trance-formation.com/\n}}\n'''Cathy O'Brien''' or '''Cathleen Ann O'Brien''' (born December 4, 1957, [[Muskegon, Michigan]])<ref name=obrien1/> is an [[United States|American]] author and speaker who claims to be a victim of a government [[mind control]] program called ''Project Monarch'' which she alleges was part of the [[CIA|CIA's]] [[Project MKUltra]].<ref name=Versluis1>{{cite book |last = Versluis | first = A |title=The new inquisitions: heretic-hunting and the intellectual origins of modern totalitarianism |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford [Oxfordshire] |year=2006|isbn=0-19-530637-6 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate= 2008-10-20| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=vchgWeG7YawC&printsec=frontcover | page =  173 }}</ref><ref name=deyoung1>{{cite book |last = de Young | first = M | authorlink = Mary de Young | title = The day care ritual abuse moral panic |publisher=McFarland |location=Jefferson, N.C |year=2004|isbn=0-7864-1830-3 |oclc= |doi=  | accessdate = 2008-10-20| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_e8ZkJBtz0EC&printsec=frontcover | page = 235}}</ref><ref name=Toropov1>{{cite book |author=Toropov B | title= The complete idiot's guide to urban legends |publisher=Alpha Books |location=Indianapolis, Ind | year = 2001|isbn=0-02-864007-1 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate= 2008-10-20 | url = https://books.google.com/?id=OUkNsFNwUSEC&printsec=frontcover | page = 221}}</ref><ref name=Barkun1>{{cite book |author=Barkun, Michael |title=A culture of conspiracy: apocalyptic visions in contemporary America |publisher=University of California Press |location=Berkeley |year=2003|isbn=0-520-23805-2 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate= 2008-10-20 | url = https://archive.org/details/cultureofconspir0000bark |url-access=registration |page = [https://archive.org/details/cultureofconspir0000bark/page/76 76]}}</ref>{{r|obrien1}} O'Brien made these assertions in ''Trance Formation of America'' (1995) and ''Access Denied: For Reasons of National Security'' (2004) which she co-authored with her husband Mark Phillips.<ref name=obrien1/> According to scholars, there is no credible evidence for O'Brien's claims and there are numerous inconsistencies with her story.<ref name=Barkun1/>\n\n== Conspiracy narrative ==\n\nIn ''Trance Formation of America'', O'Brien claims that as a child, she was first sexually abused by her father as well as by a network of child pornographers. Supposedly, she was then forced by the [[CIA]] to participate in ''Project Monarch'', which she claims is a subsection of [[Project MKUltra]] and [[Project ARTICHOKE]]. According to O'Brien, under [[hypnosis]] she was able to recall memories of sexual abuse \u2014 of both herself and her daughter \u2014 by international [[pedophile]] rings, drug barons, and [[satanists]], who allegedly used a form of \"trauma based mind control programming\" to make her a [[sex slave]].<ref name=Versluis1/><ref name=deyoung1/><ref name=Toropov1/><ref name=Barkun1/>\n\nO'Brien accuses a wide range of prominent individuals \u2014 from [[United States]], [[Canada|Canadian]], [[Mexico|Mexican]] and [[Saudi Arabian]] government officials, to stars of the [[Country and Western]] music scene \u2014 of being part of a ''Project Monarch'' conspiracy to run sex slave rings and commit child abuse.<ref>{{cite book |author=Gardell M | authorlink = Mattias Gardell |title=Gods of the blood: the pagan revival and white separatism |publisher=Duke University Press |location=Durham, N.C |year=2003 |pages= |isbn=0-8223-3071-7 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate= 2008-10-20 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=FIwwWSSL5JIC&printsec=frontcover }}</ref> For example, O'Brien claims that [[George H. W. Bush]] and [[Miguel de la Madrid]] used [[hologram]]s to appear to her in altered forms, saying that \"Bush apparently activated a hologram of the lizard-like \"alien\" which provided the illusion of Bush transforming like a chameleon before my eyes. In retrospect, I understand that Bush had been painstakingly careful in positioning our seats in order that the hologram's effectiveness be maximized.\"{{r|obrien1|page=167, 211}}\n\nO'Brien claims ''Project Monarch'' caused her to develop [[dissociative identity disorder|multiple personality disorder]] but during alternate personality episodes, she has [[photographic memory|photographic recall]].<ref name=obrien1/> O'Brien's ''Trance Formation of America'' has been credited as originating \"one of the most significant\" and \"extreme\" [[mind control]] conspiracy theories,{{r|\"Mason\"}} and her claim of links between [[satanic ritual abuse]] and MKUltra have influenced popular [[Conspiracy theory#As popular culture|conspiracy culture]].<ref name=\"Mason\"/>\n\nReligious and political scholars have criticized O'Brien's claims for their lack of any supporting evidence. David G. Robertson characterized them as symptomatic of \"baseless\" [[moral panic]] and noted that \"no-one has ever been prosecuted of such crimes nor has any corroborating material evidence ever been produced\".<ref name=\"Robertson2016\">{{cite book|author=David G. Robertson|title=UFOs, Conspiracy Theories and the New Age: Millennial Conspiracism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4ngwCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT101|date=25 February 2016|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-4742-5322-2|pages=101\u2013}}</ref> According to scholar [[Michael Barkun]], \"scholarly and journalistic treatments of MKUltra make no mention of a Project Monarch\". Barkun describes O'Brien's account as \"sensational even by the standards of conspiracy literature\" and notes that even [[black helicopter]] conspiracy theorist [[Jim Keith]] considers it \"fraudulent or delusional\".<ref name=Barkun1/> [[Jodi Dean]] cited O'Brien's claims as an example of conspiracy theorists' tendency to excessive \"leaps in imagination and willingness to deviate from common sense\".<ref name=\"Dean2002\">{{cite book|author=Jodi Dean|title=Publicity's Secret: How Technoculture Capitalizes on Democracy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vPPAAYt4xlgC&pg=PA49|year=2002|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=0-8014-8678-5|pages=49\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\nO'Brien self-publishes her books.<ref>{{cite web |title=Order Directly from Mark & Cathy >> TRANCE Formation Of America |url=https://trance-formation.com/buy-cathy-obrien-books-official/ |website=trance-formation.com |accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n* {{cite book |last2=Phillips|first2= Mark | last1 = O'Brien | first1 = Cathy |title=Trance Formation of America |publisher=Reality Marketing, Incorporated |location= |year=1995 |pages= |isbn= |oclc= |doi= |accessdate= 2013-08-20 | url = https://archive.org/details/pdfy-HcPPLE0KFkFAPsQ4/page/n7/mode/2up | format = pdf }}\n* {{cite book | title = Access Denied: For Reasons of National Security | year = 2004 | isbn = 0-9660165-3-X | last = O'Brien | first = C | publisher = Reality Marketing, Incorporated }}\n* {{cite book | title = PTSD: Time to Heal| year = 2017 | isbn = 978-0-69277641-4 | last = O'Brien | first = C | publisher = Reality Marketing, Incorporated }}\n\n==See also==\n* [[The Corley Conspiracy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Mason\">{{cite book |last=Mason |first=Fran |author-link1= |year=2003 |chapter=Mind Control |trans-chapter= |chapterurl= |chapter-format= |editor-last=Knight |editor-first=Peter |title=Conspiracy Theories in American History |chapter-url=http://cha3u.pbworks.com/w/file/fetch/45668088/Conspiracy%20Theories%20in%20American%20History%20%282003%29.pdf |location=Santa Barbara, California |publisher=ABC-CLIO, Inc. |pages=483, 486\u2013487|isbn=9781576078129 |access-date=November 4, 2015 |ref={{harvid|Conspiracy Theories in American History|1979}}}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=obrien1>{{cite book |last2=Phillips|first2= Mark | last1 = O'Brien | first1 = Cathy |title=Trance Formation of America |publisher=Reality Marketing, Incorporated |location= |year=1995 |pages= |isbn=0-9660165-4-8 |oclc= |doi= | accessdate = 2008-10-20 | url = https://archive.org/details/TranceformationOfAmerica | format = pdf }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Satanic ritual abuse}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Obrien, Cathy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:American women writers]]\n[[Category:American conspiracy theorists]]\n[[Category:Mind control]]\n[[Category:Satanic ritual abuse]]\n[[Category:Project MKUltra]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name   = Cathy O'Brien\n| image     = \n| image_size     = 150px\n| caption  = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1957|12|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Muskegon, Michigan]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| known_for = Conspiracy theorist, statements alleging victimization by ''Project Monarch''\n| education      =\n| occupation     = Writer, speaker\n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| spouse         = Mark Phillips\n| parents        = Earl M. O'Brien<br>Carol O'Brien (n\u00e9e Tanis)\n| children       = Kelly O'Brien\n| website = http://trance-formation.com/\n}}\n'''Cathy O'Brien''' or '''Cathleen Ann O'Brien''' (born December 4, 1957, [[Muskegon, Michigan]])<ref name=obrien1/> is an [[United States|American]] author and speaker who claims to be a victim of a government [[mind control]] program called ''Project Monarch'' which she alleges was part of the [[CIA|CIA's]] [[Project MKUltra]].<ref nam