kitschie-award|accessdate=14 February 2014|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=13 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Novels===\n\n====For ''Hacker'' (1995)====\n* 1994, [[WH Smith Mind-Boggling Book Award|W.H. Smith Mind Boggling Book of the Year Award]].<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 1994, [[The Daily Telegraph|Young Telegraph]]/Gimme 5 Children's Book of the Year Award.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 1995, Birmingham/TSB Children's Book Award (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n\n====For ''A.N.T.I.D.O.T.E'' (1997)====\n* 1997, Stockport Children's Book of the Year Award (Key Stage 3 category).<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 1997, Stockton-on-Tees Children's Book Award (shortlisted).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 1998, Sheffield Children's Book Award (highly commended).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2001, Stockport Schools Book Award (shortlisted).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n\n====For ''Pig-Heart Boy'' (1997)====\n* 1998, [[Carnegie Medal (literary award)|Carnegie Medal]] (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 1998, UKRA Award.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 1999, [[Lancashire Children's Book of the Year]] (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 1999, Wirral Paperback of the Year Award.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/><ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n\n====For ''Tell Me No Lies'' (1999)====\n* 1999, Stockport Children's Book Award (shortlisted) (Key Stage 4 category).<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/><ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n\n====For ''Dead Gorgeous'' (2002)====\n* 2003, Calderdale Book of the Year (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2003, Salford Children's Book Award (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n\n====For books in the ''Noughts & Crosses'' series====\n* 2002, [[Lancashire Children's Book of the Year]].<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/><ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2002, [[Red House Children's Book Award]].<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/><ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2002, Sheffield Children's Book Award.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/><ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2003, Wirral Paperback of the Year Award.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/><ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2004, Fantastic Fiction Award.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 2005, Berkshire Book Award (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2005, [[Lancashire Children's Book of the Year]] (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2005, Redbridge Teenage Book Award (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2006, [[Lancashire Children's Book of the Year]] (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2006, Staffordshire Young People's Book of the Year.<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n\n====For ''Cloud Busting'' (2004)====\n* 2004, [[Nestl\u00e9 Smarties Book Prize]] (Silver Award) (6\u20138 years category).<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 2005, Redbridge Children's Book Award (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2005, Stockport Schools Book Award (shortlisted).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2006, Nottingham Children's Book Award (shortlist) (10\u201311 years category).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2006, West Sussex Children's Book Award (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n\n====For ''Crossfire'' (2019)====\n* 2019, Costa Children\u2019s Book Award (Shortlist).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.costa.co.uk/behind-the-beans/costa-book-awards/book-awards|title=Costa Book Awards &#124; Behind the beans &#124; Costa Coffee|website=www.costa.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Television adaptations===\n\n====For ''Pig-Heart Boy''====\n* 2000, [[British Academy Television Awards|BAFTA]] Best Drama.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/><ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2000, Race and Media Best Drama Award.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 2000, [[Royal Television Society]] Award (Children's Drama category).<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 2001, Chicago TV Festival (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 2001, Prix Danube Children's Jury Prize.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n\n==== For the ''Doctor Who'' episode ''Rosa'' ====\n* 2019, [[Hugo Award]] for [[Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation#Short Form|Best Dramatic Presentation (Short Form)]], nominated <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/2019/04/2019-hugo-award-1944-retro-hugo-award-finalists/|title=2019 Hugo Award & 1944 Retro Hugo Award Finalists|date=2019-04-02|website=The Hugo Awards|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em |refs=\n<ref name=laureate>\n[http://www.childrenslaureate.org.uk<!--/previous-laureates-->/malorie-blackman/ \"Malorie Blackman\"]. Children's Laureate (childrenslaureate.org.uk). [[Booktrust]]. Retrieved 28 September 2013.</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{British council|malorie-blackman}}\n* {{isfdb name}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* [http://www.literaturfestival.com/archive/participants/authors/2008/malorie-blackman-en?set_language=en Short Biography]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-culture}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[Julia Donaldson]] }}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[Children's Laureate|Children's Laureate of the United Kingdom]] |years=2013\u20132015 }}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Chris Riddell]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blackman, Malorie}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Greenwich]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English children's writers]]\n[[Category:English science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English television writers]]\n[[Category:English dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:Women television writers]]\n[[Category:British science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:British women short story writers]]\n[[Category:British women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:People from Beckenham]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Black British writers]]\n[[Category:British Children's Laureate]]\n[[Category:20th-century English novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century English novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:Women science fiction and fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:English women novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British short story writers]]\n[[Category:English people of Barbadian descent]]\n[[Category:English women non-fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Malorie Blackman\n| honorific-suffix = [[OBE]]\n| image = Maloriesmall.jpg\n| caption = <!-- Blackman when? -->\n| imagesize = 200px\n| birth_name = Malorie Blackman\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|2|8|49|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Clapham]], [[London]], England\n| nationality = British\n| occupation = Author\n| genre = Children's literature, [[science fiction]], [[Mystery fiction|mystery]], [[thriller (genre)|thriller]] and [[Horror fiction|horror]]; poetry\n| period = \n| movement = \n| website = {{URL|www.malorieblackman.co.uk/}}\n}}\n\n'''Malorie Blackman''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}} was born 8 February 1962. She is a British writer who held the position of [[Children's Laureate]] from 2013 to 2015.<ref name=laureate/> She primarily writes literature and television drama for children and young adults. She has used science fiction to explore social and ethical issues. Her critically and popularly acclaimed [[Noughts & Crosses series|''Noughts and Crosses'' series]] uses the setting of a fictional dystopia to explore racism. Her book \"Pig Heart Boy\" sold out within a week of publishing it. {{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Early life==\nBlackman was born in [[Clapham]], [[London]]. Her parents were both from [[Barbados]]. At school, she wanted to be an English teacher, but she grew up to become a [[system programming|systems programmer]] instead.<ref name=\"Penguin authors\">{{cite web\n |last        = Blackman\n |first       = Malorie\n |title       = Malorie Blackman\n |work        = Penguin UK Authors\n |publisher   = Penguin Books Ltd.\n |date        = 1995\u20132007\n |url         = http://www.penguin.co.uk/nf/Author/AuthorPage/0,,0_1000003969,00.html\n |accessdate  = 23 March 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070419075514/http://www.penguin.co.uk/nf/Author/AuthorPage/0,,0_1000003969,00.html\n |archivedate = 19 April 2007\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Craig interview\">{{cite web\n |last=Craig \n |first=Amanda \n |authorlink=Amanda Craig \n |title=Malorie Blackman: the world in photographic negative \n |work=[[The Times]] \n |publisher=Times Newspapers Limited \n |date=January 2004 \n |url=http://www.amandacraig.com/pages/journalism/interviews/malorie_blackman.htm \n |accessdate=27 March 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061202031831/http://www.amandacraig.com/pages/journalism/interviews/malorie_blackman.htm \n |archivedate=2 December 2006 \n}}</ref> She earned an [[Higher National Certificate|HNC]] at [[University of Greenwich|Thames Polytechnic]] and is a graduate of the [[National Film and Television School]].<ref name=\"Penguin authors\" /><ref>{{cite web\n  | title = Malorie Blackman\n  | work = 40 artists, 40 days\n  | publisher = [[Tate|Tate Online]]\n  | year = 2006\n  | url = http://www2.tate.org.uk/40artists40days/malorie_blackman.html\n  | accessdate = 28 March 2007 }}</ref>\n\nShe married Neil Morrison in 1992 and their daughter, Elizabeth Morrison, was born in 1995.<ref name=\"Craig interview\"/>\n\n==Author==\nMalorie blackman had her book \"New Windmills Spring\" sold out within a week of publishing it.\n\n  | title = Full Record\n  | work = [[British Library]] Integrated Catalogue\n  | publisher = The British Library Board\n  | url = http://catalogue.bl.uk\n  | accessdate = 28 March 2007 }}</ref> Ever since, she has written more than 60 children's books, including novels and short story collections, and also television [[screenplays|scripts]] and a [[theatre|stage play]].<ref name=\"British Library catalogue\">{{cite web\n\n  | title = Full Record\n  | work = [[British Library]] Integrated Catalogue\n  | publisher = The British Library Board\n  | url = http://catalogue.bl.uk\n  | accessdate = 28 March 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\">{{cite web\n |title       = Malorie Blackman\n |work        = Contemporary Writers\n |publisher   = [[British Council]]\n |year        = 2007\n |url         = http://www.contemporarywriters.com/authors/?p=auth519D6BC107d6922CB1VoU30CEDE6\n |accessdate  = 23 March 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070411063835/http://www.contemporarywriters.com/authors/?p=auth519D6BC107d6922CB1VoU30CEDE6\n |archivedate = 11 April 2007\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nHer work has won over 15 awards.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\" /><ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\">{{cite web\n  | title = Awards and Prizes\n  | work = Kids at Random House\n  | publisher = Random House Children's Books\n  | url = http://www.randomhouse.co.uk/childrens/grownups/prizes/prizes.htm\n  | accessdate = 23 March 2007 }}</ref> Blackman's television scripts include episodes of the long-running children's drama ''[[Byker Grove]]'' as well as television adaptations of her novels ''Whizziwig'' and ''Pig-Heart Boy''.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\" /> She became the first [[person of colour]] writer to work on ''[[Doctor Who]]'' in its entire history (something almost accomplished by [[Robin Mukherjee (writer)|Robin Mukherjee]] 29 years earlier, during the run of the original series with the unmade ''[[List of unmade Doctor Who serials and films#Alixion|Alixion]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/tv/doctor-who/20863/doctor-who-episodes-and-spin-offs-that-never-happened|title=Doctor Who episodes and spin-offs that never happened|author=James T|date=19 June 2011|publisher=Den of Geek}}</ref> Her books have been translated into over 15 languages including [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Welsh language|Welsh]], [[German language|German]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]] and [[French language|French]].\n\nBlackman's award-winning ''Noughts & Crosses series'', exploring love, racism and violence, is set in a fictional [[utopian and dystopian fiction|dystopia]]. Explaining her choice of title, in a 2007 interview for the [[BBC]]'s ''Blast'' website, Blackman said that [[tic-tac-toe|noughts and crosses]] is \"one of those games that nobody ever plays after [[childhood]], because nobody ever wins\".<ref name=\"BBC Blast interview\">{{cite web\n  | title = Malorie Blackman \u2013 Children and Young People's Writer\n  | work = Blast\n  | publisher = BBC\n  | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/blast/about/ask/mblackman_transcript.shtml\n  | accessdate = 23 March 2007 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> In an interview for ''[[The Times]]'', Blackman said that before writing ''Noughts & Crosses'', her [[protagonist]]s' [[ethnic group|ethnicities]] had never been central to the plots of her books.<ref name=\"Craig interview\"/> She has also said, \"I wanted to show black children just getting on with their lives, having adventures, and solving their dilemmas, like the characters in all the books I read as a child.\"<ref name=\"Penguin authors\" />\n\nBlackman eventually decided to address racism directly.<ref name=\"Craig interview\"/><ref name=\"BBC Blast interview\" /> She reused some details from her own experience, including an occasion when she needed a [[bandage|plaster]] and found they were designed to be inconspicuous only on white people's skin.<ref name=\"Craig interview\"/> ''The Times'' interviewer [[Amanda Craig]] speculated about the delay for the ''Noughts & Crosses'' series to be  published in the [[United States]]: \"though there was considerable interest, 9/11 killed off the possibility of publishing any book describing what might drive someone to become a terrorist\".<ref name=\"Craig interview\"/> ''Noughts and Crosses'' is now available in the US published under the title ''Black & White'' (Simon & Schuster Publishers, 2005).\n\n''Noughts & Crosses'' was No. 61 on the [[Big Read]] list, a 2003 BBC survey to find \"The Nation's Best-Loved Book\", with more votes than ''[[A Tale of Two Cities]]'', several [[Terry Pratchett]] novels and ''[[Lord of the Flies]]''.\n\nShe was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the 2008 Birthday Honours.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58729 |date=14 June 2008 |page=9 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, Blackman was announced as the new Children's Laureate, succeeding [[Julia Donaldson]].<ref>Martin Chilton, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/booknews/10094538/Malorie-Blackman-is-new-Childrens-Laureate.html \"Malorie Blackman is new Children\u2019s Laureate\"], ''The Telegraph'', 4 June 2013.</ref><ref>Michelle Pauli, [https://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2013/jun/04/malorie-blackman-childrens-laureate \"Malorie Blackman is the new children's laureate\"], Children's Books, ''The Guardian'', 4 June 2013.</ref>.\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMalorie Blackman lives with her husband Neil and daughter Elizabeth in [[Kent]], England. In her free time, she likes to play her piano, compose, play computer games and write poetry.<ref>Preface to ''Tell Me No Lies''.</ref> She is the subject of a biography for children by [[Verna Wilkins]].<ref>Verna Wilkins, [http://www.randomhouse.co.uk/editions/malorie-blackman-biography/9781870516495 ''Malorie Blackman \u2013 Author''] Black Stars series, Tamarind/Random House, 2008.</ref>\n\nIn March 2014, Blackman joined other prominent authors in supporting the [[Let books be books|Let Books Be Books]] campaign, which seeks to stop children\u2019s books being labelled as 'for girls' or 'for boys'.<ref name=\"BBC 17 March 2014\" >{{cite news |last= Masters |first= Tim |title= Campaign over gender-specific books gains support |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-26612080|accessdate=24 November 2014 |website= BBC News |date=17 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, Malorie Blackman was one of 200 public figures who were signatories to a letter to ''[[The Guardian]]'' opposing [[Scottish independence]] in the run-up to September's [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|referendum on that issue]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/07/celebrities-open-letter-scotland-independence-full-text |title=Celebrities' open letter to Scotland \u2013 full text and list of signatories &#124; Politics |work=theguardian.com |date=7 August 2014 |accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n\n===Published works===\n\n====Novels for young adults and children====\n* ''Not So Stupid!: Incredible Short Stories'', The Women's Press, 1990, {{ISBN|0-7043-4924-8}}\n* ''Trust Me'', Livewire, 1992, {{ISBN|0-7043-4931-0}}. Corgi Children's, 2013, {{ISBN|0-552-56847-3}}\n* ''Words Last Forever'', Mammoth, 1998, {{ISBN|0-7497-2983-X}}\n* The [[Noughts & Crosses series]]:\n**''Noughts & Crosses'',<ref>Also published as ''Black & White'', Simon Pulse, 2007, {{ISBN|1-4169-0017-9}}</ref> Doubleday, 2001, {{ISBN|0-385-60008-9}}\n**''An Eye for an Eye'',<ref>Also published in ''Noughts & Crosses'', Corgi Children's, 2006, {{ISBN|0-552-55570-3}}</ref> Corgi Children's, 2003, {{ISBN|0-552-54925-8}}\n**''Knife Edge'', Doubleday, 2004, {{ISBN|0-385-60527-7}}\n**''Checkmate'', Doubleday, 2005, {{ISBN|0-385-60773-3}}\n**''Double Cross'', Doubleday, 6 November 2008\n**''Crossfire'', Penguin, Summer 2019\n* 'The Stuff of Nightmares'', Doubleday, 2007, {{ISBN|0-385-61043-2}}\n* ''[[Boys Don't Cry (novel)|Boys Don't Cry]]'', Doubleday Children's, 2010. Corgi Children's, 2011, {{ISBN|0-552-54862-6}}\n* ''Unheard Voices: An Anthology of Stories and Poems to Commemorate the Bicentenary Anniversary of the Abolition of the Slave Trade'', ed. Malorie Blackman, Corgi Children's, 2007, {{ISBN|0-552-55600-9}}\n* ''Noble Conflict'', Doubleday Children's, 2013, {{ISBN|0-385-61042-4}}\n====Short stories for young adults====\n* \"Humming Through My Fingers\" in the multi-author collection ''Shining on: A Collection of Stories in Aid of the Teen Cancer Trust'', Picadilly Press, 2006, {{ISBN|1-85340-893-X}}\n* Short story in the multi-author collection ''The Crew and Other Teen Fiction'', Heinemann Library, {{ISBN|0-431-01875-8}}\n\n====Novels for children====\n* ''Hacker'', Doubleday, 1992, {{ISBN|0-385-40278-3}}\n* ''Operation Gadgetman!'', Doubleday, 1993, {{ISBN|0-385-40337-2}}\n* ''Jack Sweettooth the 73rd'', Viking Children's Books, 1995, {{ISBN|0-670-85539-1}}\n* ''The Space Stowaway'', Ginn, 1995, {{ISBN|0-602-26393-X}}\n* ''[[Whizziwig]]'' (illustrated by Stephen Lee), Viking Children's Books, 1995, {{ISBN|0-670-85705-X}}\n* ''Thief!'', Doubleday, 1996, {{ISBN|0-552-52808-0}}\n* ''A.N.T.I.D.O.T.E'', Doubleday, 1997, {{ISBN|0-552-52839-0}}\n* ''[[Pig Heart Boy]]'', Doubleday, 1997, {{ISBN|0-385-40681-9}}\n* ''Animal Avengers'' (illustrated by Bill Greenhead and Stik), Mammoth, 1999, {{ISBN|0-7497-3557-0}}\n* ''Dangerous Reality'', Doubleday, 1999, {{ISBN|0-385-40680-0}}\n* ''Don't Be Afraid''<ref>Originally published 1997.</ref> (illustrated by Bob Harvey), Ginn, 1999, {{ISBN|0-602-27549-0}}\n* ''Forbidden Game'', Puffin Books, 1999, {{ISBN|0-14-130321-2}}\n* ''Hostage''<ref>Also published as ''4u2read.ok Hostage'', Barrington Stoke, 2002,\n{{ISBN|1-84299-056-X}}, and as a \"Close Look, Quick Look\" photocopiable version for teachers, Barrington Stoke, 2004, {{ISBN|1-84299-236-8}}</ref> (illustrated by Derek Brazell), Barrington Stoke, 1999, {{ISBN|1-902260-12-0}}\n* ''Tell Me No Lies'', Macmillan Children's Books, 1999, {{ISBN|0-333-72645-6}}\n* ''Whizziwig Returns'' (illustrated by Stephen Lee), Puffin, 1999, {{ISBN|0-14-130458-8}}\n* ''Dead Gorgeous'', Doubleday, 2002, {{ISBN|0-385-60009-7}}\n* ''[[Cloud Busting]]'', Doubleday, 2004, {{ISBN|0-385-60796-2}}\n* ''The Deadly Dare Mysteries'' (contents: ''Deadly Dare'', ''Computer Ghost'', ''Lie Detectives''; illustrated by Neil Chapman), Corgi Children's, 2005, {{ISBN|0-552-55353-0}}\n* ''Whizziwig and Whizziwig Returns''<ref>Originally published separately as ''Whizziwig'', 1995, and ''Whizzywhig Returns'', 1999</ref> (illustrated by Stephen Lee), Corgi Children's, 2005, {{ISBN|0-440-86657-X}}\n* [[Seventh Doctor|''Doctor Who]]: The Ripple Effect'', Puffin, 2013 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwho.tv/whats-new/article/malorie-blackman-pens-seventh-doctor-and-daleks-story |title=Malorie Blackman pens Seventh Doctor and Daleks story &#124; Articles &#124; Doctor Who |publisher=Doctorwho.tv |date=2 July 2013 |accessdate=22 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Short stories for children====\n* \"Contact\" in the multi-author collection ''Out of This World: Stories of Virtual Reality'' (chosen by Wendy Cooling), Dolphin, 1997, {{ISBN|1-85881-602-5}}\n* ''Aesop's Fables'' (retold by Malorie Blackman, illustrated by Patrice Aggs), Scholastic, 1998, {{ISBN|0-590-54382-2}}\n* \"Dare to be Different\" (illustrated by Jane Ray) in the multi-author collection ''Dare to be Different'', Bloomsbury Publishing, 1999, {{ISBN|0-7475-4021-7}}\n* \"Peacemaker\" in the multi-author collection ''Peacemaker and Other Stories'' (illustrated by Peter Richardson and David Hine), Heinemann Educational, 1999, {{ISBN|0-435-11600-2}}\n\n====Books for new readers====\n* The Betsey Biggalow stories:\n** ''Betsey Biggalow the Detective'' (illustrated by Lis Toft), Piccadilly Press, 1992, {{ISBN|1-85340-163-3}}\n** ''Betsey Biggalow is Here!'' (illustrated by Lis Toft), Piccadilly Press, 1992, {{ISBN|1-85340-172-2}}\n** ''Hurricane Betsey'' (illustrated by Lis Toft), Piccadilly Press, 1993, {{ISBN|1-85340-199-4}}\n** ''Magic Betsey'' (illustrated by Lis Toft), Piccadilly Press, 1994, {{ISBN|1-85340-237-0}}\n** ''Betsey's Birthday Surprise'' (illustrated by Lis Toft), Piccadilly Press, 1996, {{ISBN|0-590-55864-1}}\n*The Girl Wonder series:\n** ''Girl Wonder and the Terrific Twins'' (illustrated by Pat Ludlow), Orion Children's Books, 1991, {{ISBN|0-575-05048-9}}\n** ''Girl Wonder's Winter Adventures'' (illustrated by Lis Toft), Orion Children's Books, 1992, {{ISBN|0-575-05383-6}}\n** ''Girl Wonder to the Rescue'' (illustrated by Lis Toft), Gollancz, 1994, {{ISBN|0-575-05774-2}}\n** ''The Amazing Adventures of Girl Wonder'' (illustrated by Lis Toft), Barn Owl Books, 2003, {{ISBN|1-903015-27-8}}\n* The Puzzle Planet adventures:\n** ''Peril on Planet Pellia'' (illustrated by Patrice Aggs), Orchard Books, 1996, {{ISBN|1-85213-935-8}}\n** ''The Mellion Moon Mystery'' (illustrated by Patrice Aggs), Orchard Books, 1996, {{ISBN|1-85213-936-6}}\n** ''The Secret of the Terrible Hand'' (illustrated by Patrice Aggs), Orchard Books, 1996, {{ISBN|1-86039-370-5}}\n** ''Quasar Quartz Quest'' (illustrated by Patrice Aggs) Orchard Books, 1996, {{ISBN|1-85213-938-2}}\n* The Longman Book Project (with translations to Welsh):\n** ''Rachel versus Bonecrusher the Mighty'', Longman, 1994, {{ISBN|0-582-12151-5}}\n** ''Rachel and the Difference Thief'' (illustrated by Kim Harley), Longman, 1994, {{ISBN|0-582-12152-3}}\n** ''Crazy Crocs'' (with Alexander McCall Smith and Sally-Ann Lever), Longman, 1994, {{ISBN|0-582-12208-2}}\n* ''Elaine You're a Brat!'' <ref>Also published as ''Ellie, and the Cat!'', Orchard Books, 2005, {{ISBN|1-84362-391-9}}</ref> (illustrated by Doffy Weir), Orchard Books, 1991, {{ISBN|1-85213-365-1}}\n* ''My Friend's a Gris-Quok'' (illustrated by Philip Hopman), Scholastic, 1994, {{ISBN|0-590-55864-1}}\n* ''Grandma Gertie's Haunted Handbag'' (illustrated by David Price), Heinemann, 1996, {{ISBN|0-434-97225-8}}\n* ''Space Race'' (illustrated by Colin Mier), Corgi Children's, 1997, {{ISBN|0-552-54542-2}}\n* ''Fangs'' (illustrated by Tony Blundell), Orchard Books, 1998, {{ISBN|1-86039-734-4}}\n* ''Snow Dog'' (illustrated by Sabrina Good), Corgi Children's, 2001, {{ISBN|0-552-54703-4}}\n* ''The Monster Crisp-Guzzler'' (illustrated by Saynab Abdalla), Corgi Children's, 2002, {{ISBN|0-552-54783-2}}\n* ''Sinclair, Wonder Bear'' (illustrated by Deborah Allwright), Egmont Books, 2003, {{ISBN|1-4052-0589-X}}\n\n====Picture books====\n* ''That New Dress'' <ref>Also published as ''A New Dress for Maya'', Gary Stevens Publishing, 1992, {{ISBN|0-8368-0713-8}}</ref> (illustrated by Rhian Nest James), Hodder Wayland, 1991, {{ISBN|0-7500-0442-8}}\n* ''Mrs Spoon's Family'' (illustrated by Jan McCafferty), Andersen Press, 1995, {{ISBN|0-86264-582-4}}\n* ''Dizzy's Walk'' (illustrated by Pamela Venus), Tamarind, 1999, {{ISBN|1-870516-41-9}}\n* ''Marty Monster'' (illustrated by Kim Harley), Tamarind, 1999, {{ISBN|1-870516-42-7}}\n* ''I Want a Cuddle!'' (illustrated by Joanne Partis), Orchard Books, 2001, {{ISBN|1-84121-823-5}}\n* ''Jessica Strange'' (with Alison Bartlett), Hodder Children's Books, 2002, {{ISBN|0-340-77963-2}}\n* Contributed to ''A Christmas Tree of Stories'', Scholastic Press, 1999, {{ISBN|0-439-01192-2}}\n\n===Television scripts===\n* Episodes of ''[[Byker Grove]]''\n* Episodes of ''[[Whizziwig]]''\n* Episodes of ''[[Pig Heart Boy]]''\n* Episode of ''[[Doctor Who]]'' \u2014 \"[[Rosa (Doctor Who)|Rosa]]\" (2018), co-written with [[Chris Chibnall]]\nHer novel ''Operation Gadgetman!'' was also adapted into a 1996 TV movie directed by [[Jim Goddard]] and starring [[Marina Sirtis]].\n\n===Stage plays===\n*''The Amazing Rob The Mechanic''\n*''Noughts and Crosses''\n\n===Radio scripts===\n*''Noughts and Crosses''\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n===Body of work===\n* 1997, Excelle/Write Thing Children's Author of the Year Award.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 2005, [[Children's Book Circle]]'s [[Eleanor Farjeon Award]].<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2013, [[The Kitschies]] Black Tentacle for \"outstanding achievement in encouraging and elevating the conversation around genre literature\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Flood|first=Alison|title=Ruth Ozeki beats Thomas Pynchon to top Kitschie award|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/feb/13/ruth-ozeki-thomas-pynchon-kitschie-award|accessdate=14 February 2014|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=13 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Novels===\n\n====For ''Hacker'' (1995)====\n* 1994, [[WH Smith Mind-Boggling Book Award|W.H. Smith Mind Boggling Book of the Year Award]].<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 1994, [[The Daily Telegraph|Young Telegraph]]/Gimme 5 Children's Book of the Year Award.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 1995, Birmingham/TSB Children's Book Award (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n\n====For ''A.N.T.I.D.O.T.E'' (1997)====\n* 1997, Stockport Children's Book of the Year Award (Key Stage 3 category).<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 1997, Stockton-on-Tees Children's Book Award (shortlisted).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 1998, Sheffield Children's Book Award (highly commended).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2001, Stockport Schools Book Award (shortlisted).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n\n====For ''Pig-Heart Boy'' (1997)====\n* 1998, [[Carnegie Medal (literary award)|Carnegie Medal]] (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 1998, UKRA Award.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 1999, [[Lancashire Children's Book of the Year]] (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 1999, Wirral Paperback of the Year Award.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/><ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n\n====For ''Tell Me No Lies'' (1999)====\n* 1999, Stockport Children's Book Award (shortlisted) (Key Stage 4 category).<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/><ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n\n====For ''Dead Gorgeous'' (2002)====\n* 2003, Calderdale Book of the Year (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2003, Salford Children's Book Award (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n\n====For books in the ''Noughts & Crosses'' series====\n* 2002, [[Lancashire Children's Book of the Year]].<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/><ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2002, [[Red House Children's Book Award]].<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/><ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2002, Sheffield Children's Book Award.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/><ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2003, Wirral Paperback of the Year Award.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/><ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2004, Fantastic Fiction Award.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 2005, Berkshire Book Award (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2005, [[Lancashire Children's Book of the Year]] (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2005, Redbridge Teenage Book Award (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2006, [[Lancashire Children's Book of the Year]] (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2006, Staffordshire Young People's Book of the Year.<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n\n====For ''Cloud Busting'' (2004)====\n* 2004, [[Nestl\u00e9 Smarties Book Prize]] (Silver Award) (6\u20138 years category).<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 2005, Redbridge Children's Book Award (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2005, Stockport Schools Book Award (shortlisted).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2006, Nottingham Children's Book Award (shortlist) (10\u201311 years category).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2006, West Sussex Children's Book Award (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n\n====For ''Crossfire'' (2019)====\n* 2019, Costa Children\u2019s Book Award (Shortlist).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.costa.co.uk/behind-the-beans/costa-book-awards/book-awards|title=Costa Book Awards &#124; Behind the beans &#124; Costa Coffee|website=www.costa.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Television adaptations===\n\n====For ''Pig-Heart Boy''====\n* 2000, [[British Academy Television Awards|BAFTA]] Best Drama.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/><ref name=\"multiple awards (second)\"/>\n* 2000, Race and Media Best Drama Award.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 2000, [[Royal Television Society]] Award (Children's Drama category).<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 2001, Chicago TV Festival (shortlist).<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n* 2001, Prix Danube Children's Jury Prize.<ref name=\"multiple awards (first)\"/>\n\n==== For the ''Doctor Who'' episode ''Rosa'' ====\n* 2019, [[Hugo Award]] for [[Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation#Short Form|Best Dramatic Presentation (Short Form)]], nominated <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/2019/04/2019-hugo-award-1944-retro-hugo-award-finalists/|title=2019 Hugo Award & 1944 Retro Hugo Award Finalists|date=2019-04-02|website=The Hugo Awards|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em |refs=\n<ref name=laureate>\n[http://www.childrenslaureate.org.uk<!--/previous-laureates-->/malorie-blackman/ \"Malorie Blackman\"]. Children's Laureate (childrenslaureate.org.uk). [[Booktrust]]. Retrieved 28 September 2013.</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{British council|malorie-blackman}}\n* {{isfdb name}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* [http://www.literaturfestival.com/archive/participants/authors/2008/malorie-blackman-en?set_language=en Short Biography]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-culture}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[Julia Donaldson]] }}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[Children's Laureate|Children's Laureate of the United Kingdom]] |years=2013\u20132015 }}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Chris Riddell]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blackman, Malorie}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Greenwich]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English children's writers]]\n[[Category:English science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English television writers]]\n[[Category:English dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:Women television writers]]\n[[Category:British science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:British women short story writers]]\n[[Category:British women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:People from Beckenham]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Black British writers]]\n[[Category:British Children's Laureate]]\n[[Category:20th-century English novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century English novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:Women science fiction and fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:English women novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British short story writers]]\n[[Category:English people of Barbadian descent]]\n[[Category:English women non-fiction writers]]\n", "name_user": "90.254.113.243", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malorie_Blackman"}
{"title_page": "Adriana Benitez", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|Ben\u00edtez|Perugache}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Adriana Ben\u00edtez\n|image=\n|birth_name=Adriana Fernanda Benitez Perugache\n|birth_place=[[Pasto, Colombia|Pasto]]\n|birth_date=October 31, 1975\n|death_place=Pasto\n|death_date={{Death date and age|2000|10|14|1975|10|31}}\n|nationality=[[Colombia]]\n|occupation=Student\n|known_for=Murder\n}}\n\n'''Adriana Fernanda Benitez Perugache''' (31 October 1975 \u2013 14 October 2000) was a Colombian student leader and founder of Radicales Libres who was murdered by the [[United Self-Defense Forces of Colombia]]. She became known as the \"Flower of the [[University of Nari\u00f1o|University (of Nari\u00f1o)]]\" ({{lang-es|La Flora de la Universidad}}).\n\n==Biography==\nAdriana Ben\u00edtez was born on 31 October 1975 the third of five sisters in San Rafael Hospital, [[Pasto, Colombia|Pasto]], [[Colombia]]. After she graduated [[high school]], she entered the [[University of Nari\u00f1o]] to study [[economics]]. At 18, she had a child and was obliged to enter the workforce to pay for her tuition and family, which was difficult because of low wages. In this environment, she became a [[socialist]] and began meeting and working with local women to at first procure items for families and then improved working conditions, rights, and benefits.<ref name=silence>{{cite web|title=ADRIANA FERNANDA BENITEZ|url=https://vidassilenciadas.org/adriana-fernanda-benitez/|website=vidassilenciadas.org|publisher=Vidas Silenciadas|accessdate=20 November 2017|language=es}}</ref>\n\nAt the University-level, she founded the student group Radicales Libres and led student demonstrations against the {{Interlanguage link|National Development Plan (Colombia)|es|Plan Nacional de Desarrollo (Colombia)|lt=1999 National Development Plan}} and organized the Departmental Forum Against the Colombia Plan. She also advocated for the reduction of motor vehicles in Pasto and organized protests against [[Plan Colombia]].<ref name=memory>{{cite web|title=Memorias de la represi\u00f3n: persecuci\u00f3n al movimiento estudiantil en el Departamento de Nari\u00f1o (Colombia)|url=http://movimientodevictimas.org/~nuncamas/images/stories/pdf/movimiento%20estudiantil%20en%20el%20departamento.pdf|website=movimientodevictimas.org|publisher=Memorias de la Represi\u00f3n|accessdate=20 November 2017|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304121702/http://movimientodevictimas.org/~nuncamas/images/stories/pdf/movimiento%20estudiantil%20en%20el%20departamento.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status = dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Murder==\nOn 14 October 2000, Ben\u00edtez and fellow student Mart\u00edn Emilio Rodr\u00edguez were shot dead on the Plaza de Nari\u00f1o in Pasto by Guillermo P\u00e9rez Alzate, alias \"Pablo Sevillano,\" a [[United Self-Defense Forces of Colombia]] (AUC) gunman acting on the orders of [[Carlos Casta\u00f1o Gil]] while she was meeting with local women. The motive for the shooting was that she had \"worked with [[FARC]] in the [[El Cagu\u00e1n DMZ]].\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Fiscal\u00eda imputar\u00e1 35 homicidios a 'Pablo Sevillano'|url=http://www.verdadabierta.com/justicia-y-paz/extraditados/1338-pablo-sevillano-confeso-asesinato-de-29-personas-en-narino|accessdate=20 November 2017|work=Verdadabierta|date=10 June 2009|language=es}}</ref> While exiting a restaurant, P\u00e9rez and an accomplice exited a red van and shot Ben\u00edtez and Rodr\u00edguez in the back and then fled to the other side of the square to re-enter the van and escape.<ref name=silence/>\n\nBen\u00edtez's murder came at a time when the organized student body at the [[University of Nari\u00f1o]] had been strengthened by their demonstrations in 1998 and 1999 against the government of [[Andr\u00e9s Pastrana Arango]]. The organized students, already identified by right-wing paramilitaries as a potential ally to left-wing guerrillas and considered by the AUC since 199 to be \"infiltrated,\" began to more freely associate with other leftist organizations.<ref name=silence/>\n\n==Legacy==\nOne of the female dormitories at the [[National University of Colombia at Manizales]] is named after Ben\u00edtez.<ref>{{cite news|title=Adriana Ben\u00edtez y Jorge Eli\u00e9cer Gait\u00e1n recibir\u00e1n a 25 estudiantes for\u00e1neos|url=http://agenciadenoticias.unal.edu.co/nc/detalle/article/adriana-benitez-y-jorge-eliecer-gaitan-recibiran-a-25-estudiantes-foraneos.html|accessdate=20 November 2017|work=Noticias Universidad|publisher=[[National University of Colombia at Manizales]]|date=28 August 2009|language=es}}</ref>\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Benitez, Adriana}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:United Self-Defense Forces of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Colombian activists]]\n[[Category:Colombian women activists]]\n[[Category:Assassinated activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Spanish name|Ben\u00edtez|Perugache}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Adriana Ben\u00edtez\n|image=\n|birth_name=Adriana Fernanda Benitez Perugache\n|birth_place=[[Pasto, Colombia|Pasto]]\n|birth_date=October 31, 1975\n|death_place=Pasto\n|death_date={{Death date and age|2000|10|14|1975|10|31}}\n|nationality=[[Colombia]]\n|occupation=Student\n|known_for=Murder\n}}\n\n'''Adriana Fernanda Benitez Perugache''' (31 October 1975 \u2013 14 October 2000) was a Colombian student leader and founder of Radicales Libres who was murdered by the [[United Self-Defense Forces of Colombia]]. She became known as the \"Flower of the [[University of Nari\u00f1o|University (of Nari\u00f1o)]]\" ({{lang-es|La Flora de la Unversidad}}).\n\n==Biography==\nAdriana Ben\u00edtez was born on 31 October 1975 the third of five sisters in San Rafael Hospital, [[Pasto, Colombia|Pasto]], [[Colombia]]. After she graduated [[high school]], she entered the [[University of Nari\u00f1o]] to study [[economics]]. At 18, she had a child and was obliged to enter the workforce to pay for her tuition and family, which was difficult because of low wages. In this environment, she became a [[socialist]] and began meeting and working with local women to at first procure items for families and then improved working conditions, rights, and benefits.<ref name=silence>{{cite web|title=ADRIANA FERNANDA BENITEZ|url=https://vidassilenciadas.org/adriana-fernanda-benitez/|website=vidassilenciadas.org|publisher=Vidas Silenciadas|accessdate=20 November 2017|language=es}}</ref>\n\nAt the University-level, she founded the student group Radicales Libres and led student demonstrations against the {{Interlanguage link|National Development Plan (Colombia)|es|Plan Nacional de Desarrollo (Colombia)|lt=1999 National Development Plan}} and organized the Departmental Forum Against the Colombia Plan. She also advocated for the reduction of motor vehicles in Pasto and organized protests against [[Plan Colombia]].<ref name=memory>{{cite web|title=Memorias de la represi\u00f3n: persecuci\u00f3n al movimiento estudiantil en el Departamento de Nari\u00f1o (Colombia)|url=http://movimientodevictimas.org/~nuncamas/images/stories/pdf/movimiento%20estudiantil%20en%20el%20departamento.pdf|website=movimientodevictimas.org|publisher=Memorias de la Represi\u00f3n|accessdate=20 November 2017|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304121702/http://movimientodevictimas.org/~nuncamas/images/stories/pdf/movimiento%20estudiantil%20en%20el%20departamento.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status = dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Murder==\nOn 14 October 2000, Ben\u00edtez and fellow student Mart\u00edn Emilio Rodr\u00edguez were shot dead on the Plaza de Nari\u00f1o in Pasto by Guillermo P\u00e9rez Alzate, alias \"Pablo Sevillano,\" a [[United Self-Defense Forces of Colombia]] (AUC) gunman acting on the orders of [[Carlos Casta\u00f1o Gil]] while she was meeting with local women. The motive for the shooting was that she had \"worked with [[FARC]] in the [[El Cagu\u00e1n DMZ]].\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Fiscal\u00eda imputar\u00e1 35 homicidios a 'Pablo Sevillano'|url=http://www.verdadabierta.com/justicia-y-paz/extraditados/1338-pablo-sevillano-confeso-asesinato-de-29-personas-en-narino|accessdate=20 November 2017|work=Verdadabierta|date=10 June 2009|language=es}}</ref> While exiting a restaurant, P\u00e9rez and an accomplice exited a red van and shot Ben\u00edtez and Rodr\u00edguez in the back and then fled to the other side of the square to re-enter the van and escape.<ref name=silence/>\n\nBen\u00edtez's murder came at a time when the organized student body at the [[University of Nari\u00f1o]] had been strengthened by their demonstrations in 1998 and 1999 against the government of [[Andr\u00e9s Pastrana Arango]]. The organized students, already identified by right-wing paramilitaries as a potential ally to left-wing guerrillas and considered by the AUC since 199 to be \"infiltrated,\" began to more freely associate with other leftist organizations.<ref name=silence/>\n\n==Legacy==\nOne of the female dormitories at the [[National University of Colombia at Manizales]] is named after Ben\u00edtez.<ref>{{cite news|title=Adriana Ben\u00edtez y Jorge Eli\u00e9cer Gait\u00e1n recibir\u00e1n a 25 estudiantes for\u00e1neos|url=http://agenciadenoticias.unal.edu.co/nc/detalle/article/adriana-benitez-y-jorge-eliecer-gaitan-recibiran-a-25-estudiantes-foraneos.html|accessdate=20 November 2017|work=Noticias Universidad|publisher=[[National University of Colombia at Manizales]]|date=28 August 2009|language=es}}</ref>\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Benitez, Adriana}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:United Self-Defense Forces of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Colombian activists]]\n[[Category:Colombian women activists]]\n[[Category:Assassinated activists]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo fixing, replaced: Unversidad \u2192 Universidad", "url_page": "//